.TH PROCFLOW 8 "April 2026" "ProcFlow 1.1.1" "System Administration"
.
.SH NAME
procflow \- process-enriched network flow logger
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B procflow
.RB [ \-\-config
.IR PATH ]
.RB [ \-\-log\-file
.IR PATH ]
.RB [ \-\-stdout\-only ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-pam ]
.br
.B procflow
.B \-\-clear\-log
.br
.B procflow
.B \-\-version
.br
.B procflow
.B \-\-help
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B procflow
is an eBPF-based network flow monitor that captures TCP, UDP, and ICMP
connections on a Linux host and emits newline-delimited JSON records to both
stdout and a rotating log file.
.PP
Each record is enriched with host OS context: the full executable path, command
line, process name, PID, UID, username, socket inode (for Wireshark and
.BR ss (8)
correlation), network namespace (for container traffic detection), and \(em for
inbound TCP sessions such as SSH \(em the authenticated PAM username of the
connecting user.
.PP
The eBPF program is compiled at startup using BCC and loaded into the kernel.
kprobes are attached to TCP connect, accept, send, receive, and close paths;
UDP send and receive paths; raw socket send paths for ICMP/ICMPv6; and the
kernel ICMP receive path for inbound ICMP.
uprobes are attached to
.BR pam_get_item (3)
in
.I libpam.so.0
to capture authentication context.
.PP
.B procflow
must be run as root.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-config\  PATH
Read configuration from
.IR PATH .
If the file does not exist, built-in defaults are used.
Default:
.IR /etc/procflow/procflow.conf .
.TP
.BI \-\-log\-file\  PATH
Write the JSON log to
.I PATH
instead of the path specified in the config file.
Log rotation settings from the config file still apply.
Useful for ad-hoc captures without editing the config.
.TP
.B \-\-stdout\-only
Write JSON records only to stdout; do not open or rotate a log file.
Useful when piping output to other tools such as
.BR jq (1)
or
.BR filebeat (1).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-pam
Skip attaching the PAM uprobes.
Flow events are still captured with process and user context, but the
.IR authenticated_user ,
.IR pam_service ,
and
.I child_processes
fields will always be null or empty.
Use this if the PAM uprobe causes issues or PAM enrichment is not required.
.TP
.B \-\-clear\-log
Truncate the active log file in-place and remove all rotated backup files,
then exit.
The running service continues without interruption; it resumes writing from
byte 0 of the same open file descriptor.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the program version and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-help
Print a usage summary and exit.
.
.SH CONFIGURATION FILE
The configuration file uses INI format, read by Python's
.BR configparser .
A missing file is silently ignored and defaults are used.
The default location is
.IR /etc/procflow/procflow.conf .
.PP
.B [logging] section
.TP
.B log_file
Absolute path to the JSON log file.
Default:
.IR /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log .
.TP
.B max_bytes
Maximum log file size in bytes before rotation.
When the active log file reaches this size it is renamed to
.I enriched_flow.log.1
(and so on up to
.IR backup_count )
and a new file is started.
Default:
.B 52428800
(50\ MB).
.TP
.B backup_count
Number of rotated log files to retain.
With the defaults, up to 250\ MB of log history is kept on disk.
Default:
.BR 5 .
.PP
.B [tuning] section
.TP
.B pam_collect_secs
Seconds to hold an inbound TCP flow in the PAM-pending queue after the first
PAM match, to allow
.B PAM_SERVICE
to arrive after
.BR PAM_USER .
On some sshd configurations these calls are separated by a few milliseconds.
Default:
.BR 1.0 .
.TP
.B pam_window_secs
Maximum seconds to wait for any PAM match on an inbound TCP flow before
emitting the record without PAM enrichment.
Default:
.BR 15.0 .
.TP
.B flow_short_secs
TCP connections that have been open for at least this many seconds without
closing will emit a
.B flow_long_open
record at this mark.
Connections that close before this threshold emit a single
.B flow_short
record.
Default:
.BR 30.0 .
.TP
.B flow_track_secs
Maximum seconds to track an open flow before evicting it from the in-memory
table (safety fallback for connections that close without a
.B tcp_close
event being observed).
Default:
.BR 3600.0 .
.PP
.B [filter] section
.TP
.B suppress
A list of suppression rules, one per line (continuation lines must be indented
with at least one space or tab).
Each rule has the form:
.PP
.RS
.I process_name\fR,\fP dst_ip\fR,\fP dst_port
.RE
.PP
An event is dropped before being written to the log if its
.IR process ,
.IR dst_ip ,
and
.I dst_port
fields all match a rule exactly.
Other connections from the same process to different destinations are unaffected.
.PP
This is useful for breaking feedback loops when a log shipper (such as Elastic Agent)
is forwarding procflow's log file to a remote server: procflow logs those outbound
connections, which the shipper then forwards again.
Add one rule per shipper→server connection to suppress only the shipping traffic.
.PP
Example \(em suppress Elastic Agent log shipping:
.PP
.RS
.nf
[filter]
suppress =
    agentbeat, 10.10.20.18, 9200
    elastic-agent, 10.10.20.18, 8220
.fi
.RE
.PP
If the key is absent the default is no suppression.
Changes take effect after restarting the service.
.
.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
All output is newline-delimited JSON.
Records written to stdout and to the log file are identical.
.PP
.B Event types
.TP
.B flow_short
A TCP connection that closed before
.IR flow_short_secs ,
any UDP socket close, or any ICMP packet.
One record per connection; contains final byte counts.
.TP
.B flow_long_open
Emitted once a TCP connection has been open for
.I flow_short_secs
without closing.
TX/RX byte counts are a snapshot at this moment, not final values.
A corresponding
.B flow_long_closed
record follows when the connection closes.
Paired to
.B flow_long_closed
via
.BR session_id .
.TP
.B flow_long_closed
Emitted when a long-lived TCP connection that generated a
.B flow_long_open
record finally closes.
TX/RX byte counts are the connection totals.
.TP
.B connect_failed
Emitted when an outbound TCP connection attempt fails.
Contains a
.I connect_error
field with the error name
.RB ( ECONNREFUSED ,
.BR ETIMEDOUT ,
.BR ENETUNREACH ,
or
.BR EHOSTUNREACH ).
Does not appear in
.B flow_short
because the connection was never established.
.TP
.B listen_start
Emitted when a TCP socket enters the LISTEN state (i.e. after the application
calls
.BR listen (2)).
Contains
.I local_ip
and
.I local_port
instead of the usual src/dst endpoint fields.
Useful for detecting which process opened a listening port before an IDS alert
fires.
.PP
.B Fields common to all TCP and UDP events
.TP
.B timestamp
ISO 8601 timestamp (UTC) generated in userspace when the event is processed.
.TP
.B direction
.B inbound
or
.BR outbound .
.TP
.B pid\fR,\fP ppid
Process ID and parent process ID of the process that owns the socket.
Null for inbound ICMP (kernel softirq context).
.TP
.B uid\fR,\fP username
Numeric UID and resolved username of the socket-owning process.
Null for inbound ICMP.
.TP
.B process
Executable name read from
.IR /proc/\fIpid\fP/comm
(the process group leader comm, not the thread name).
.B [kernel]
for inbound ICMP.
.TP
.B exe
Full path to the executable, read from
.IR /proc/\fIpid\fP/exe .
Null if the process has already exited by the time the event is processed.
Disambiguates processes that share a comm name, e.g.
.I python3
or
.IR java .
.TP
.B cmdline
Full command line from
.I /proc/\fIpid\fP/cmdline
(null-bytes replaced with spaces, truncated to 256 characters).
Null for inbound ICMP or if the process has already exited.
.TP
.B protocol
.BR TCP ,
.BR UDP ,
.BR ICMP ,
or
.BR ICMPv6 .
.TP
.B proto_hint
Application-layer protocol label derived from the destination port.
Examples:
.BR SSH ,
.BR HTTPS ,
.BR HTTP ,
.BR DNS ,
.BR QUIC ,
.BR mDNS ,
.BR NTP ,
.BR RDP .
Null when no label is defined for the port.
.TP
.B address_family
.B IPv4
or
.BR IPv6 .
.TP
.B src_ip\fR,\fP src_port\fR,\fP dst_ip\fR,\fP dst_port
Connection endpoints from the client's perspective.
For inbound flows,
.I src_ip
is the remote peer and
.I dst_ip
is the local address.
For outbound ICMP,
.I src_ip
is
.B 0.0.0.0
because the source address is selected by the routing table inside the kernel
send path after the kprobe fires.
.TP
.B sock_ino
Socket inode number.
Matches the inode shown by
.B ss \-tnp
and
.B ss \-unp
in the
.I users
column, and the inode in
.IR /proc/net/tcp .
Use this field to correlate a procflow record with a specific connection
visible in Wireshark or an IDS alert without relying on timestamp fuzzing.
Null for inbound ICMP (no userspace socket).
.TP
.B netns_ino
Network namespace inode number read from
.IR sk\->__sk_common.skc_net .
Differs from the host namespace inode
.RI ( /proc/1/ns/net )
for traffic originating from containers or other network namespaces.
Null for inbound ICMP.
.TP
.B container_traffic
Boolean.
.B true
when
.I netns_ino
is non-zero and differs from the host network namespace inode (read from
.I /proc/1/ns/net
at startup).
.B false
for host traffic.
Null for inbound ICMP.
.TP
.B tx_bytes\fR,\fP rx_bytes
Bytes sent and received on the socket, accumulated in kernel space.
On
.B flow_long_open
records these are a snapshot, not final values.
Null for ICMP (no per-socket byte accounting in the raw socket path).
.TP
.B session_id
UUID4 string linking
.B flow_long_open
and
.B flow_long_closed
records for the same connection.
.TP
.B authenticated_user
The username authenticated via PAM, if correlation succeeded.
Null for outbound flows, UDP, ICMP, or inbound flows where PAM enrichment
was not available.
.TP
.B pam_service
The PAM service name (e.g.\&
.BR sshd )
associated with the authentication.
.TP
.B child_processes
Array of PAM child process objects correlated to this flow via
.I /proc
ancestry walking.
Each object contains
.BR pid ,
.BR ppid ,
.BR process ,
.BR authenticated_user ,
.BR pam_service ,
and
.BR timestamp .
Empty for outbound flows, UDP, and ICMP.
.PP
.B Additional fields for connect_failed
.TP
.B connect_error
The error name returned by the failed connect syscall.
One of
.BR ECONNREFUSED ,
.BR ETIMEDOUT ,
.BR ENETUNREACH ,
or
.BR EHOSTUNREACH .
.PP
.B Additional fields for listen_start
.TP
.B local_ip\fR,\fP local_port
The address and port the socket is listening on.
.I local_ip
is
.B 0.0.0.0
when the socket is bound to all interfaces.
.PP
.B Additional fields for DNS flows
.TP
.B dns_query
Decoded DNS QNAME when
.I proto_hint
is
.B DNS
and procflow successfully captured the first 40 bytes of the UDP payload.
Decoded from the DNS wire format starting at offset 12 (the question section).
Null if the payload was not captured or could not be decoded (e.g.\& compressed
labels, malformed packet, or unconnected UDP socket).
.
.SH WIRESHARK AND IDS CORRELATION
.PP
.B Identifying a process behind Wireshark traffic
.RS
Note the destination IP and port from Wireshark, then query the log:
.PP
.B jq 'select(.dst_ip=="203.0.113.1" and .dst_port==443)' /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
.PP
For live traffic, correlate the socket inode directly:
.PP
.B ss \-tnp | grep 203.0.113.1
.PP
Note the inode from the
.I users
column, then:
.PP
.B jq 'select(.sock_ino==126901)' /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
.RE
.PP
.B Investigating an IDS alert
.RS
Given an alert with a timestamp and 5-tuple, query by port and time window:
.PP
.B jq 'select(.dst_port==4444 and .timestamp >= "2026-04-07T12:00:00")' /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
.PP
Use
.I container_traffic
to immediately redirect investigation to the container layer:
.PP
.B jq 'select(.container_traffic == true)' /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
.PP
Use
.I listen_start
events to identify which process opened a port before the alert fired:
.PP
.B jq 'select(.event_type == "listen_start" and .local_port == 4444)' /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
.PP
Use
.I connect_failed
events to detect local port scanners or misconfigured services:
.PP
.B jq 'select(.event_type == "connect_failed")' /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
.RE
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/procflow/procflow.conf
Default configuration file.
.TP
.I /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log
Default log file (created by the postinst script on package install).
.TP
.I /var/log/procflow/enriched_flow.log.1 \fR...\fP enriched_flow.log.5
Rotated log files.
.TP
.I /lib/systemd/system/procflow.service
systemd unit file (installed by the package).
.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
.IP \(bu 2
Linux kernel 4.9 or later (eBPF kprobes, perf buffer)
.IP \(bu 2
Root privileges
.IP \(bu 2
.B python3-bpfcc
(BCC Python bindings)
.IP \(bu 2
Kernel headers matching the running kernel:
.B linux-headers-$(uname -r)
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Run with default config as a foreground process:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow
.RE
.PP
Watch only short flows in real time:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-stdout\-only | jq 'select(.event_type == "flow_short")'
.RE
.PP
Watch DNS queries with decoded query names:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-stdout\-only | jq 'select(.dns_query != null)'
.RE
.PP
Watch for container traffic:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-stdout\-only | jq 'select(.container_traffic == true)'
.RE
.PP
Watch for failed outbound connection attempts:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-stdout\-only | jq 'select(.event_type == "connect_failed")'
.RE
.PP
Watch for new listening ports with full process context:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-stdout\-only | jq 'select(.event_type == "listen_start")'
.RE
.PP
Watch all ICMP traffic (outbound ping and inbound responses):
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-stdout\-only | jq 'select(.protocol == "ICMP")'
.RE
.PP
Run without PAM enrichment (lower overhead):
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-no\-pam
.RE
.PP
Truncate the log while the service is running:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-clear\-log
.RE
.PP
Override the log file for a one-off capture:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-log\-file /tmp/capture.log
.RE
.PP
Test an alternate config file:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo procflow \-\-config /etc/procflow/procflow.conf \-\-stdout\-only
.RE
.PP
Check version:
.PP
.RS
.B procflow \-\-version
.RE
.
.SH PERFORMANCE
The eBPF byte-counting hooks (tcp_sendmsg, tcp_cleanup_rbuf, udp_sendmsg,
udp_recvmsg) use a
.I tracked_socks
hash map as an early-exit gate: the hooks return immediately for any socket
not explicitly registered by
.BR procflow .
On a busy host with a mix of monitored and unmonitored traffic, overhead for
unrelated connections is near zero.
.PP
The BPF perf buffer is polled every 100\ ms from userspace.
PAM correlation and flow aging are also processed on this interval.
.PP
Reading
.I /proc/\fIpid\fP/exe
and
.I /proc/\fIpid\fP/cmdline
per event introduces a small amount of userspace overhead.
If the process exits before the event is processed these reads fail silently
and the fields are null.
.
.SH NOTES
The eBPF program is compiled from C source at startup using BCC.
The first startup on a machine may take several seconds.
Subsequent startups are faster due to BCC's kernel module cache.
.PP
For outbound ICMP, the
.I src_ip
field is always
.B 0.0.0.0
when the raw socket is not explicitly bound with
.BR bind (2).
The source address is selected by the kernel routing table inside the send
path, after the kprobe fires.
The
.I dst_ip
field is always populated.
.PP
Inbound ICMP events (captured via
.BR icmp_rcv )
show
.B process=[kernel]
because the kprobe fires in softirq context.
The interrupted userspace process is not the ICMP sender.
.PP
The
.I authenticated_user
field relies on sshd writing PAM credentials before the SSH session is fully
established.
In rare cases the field may be null even for authenticated sessions.
The
.I pam_window_secs
tuning parameter can be increased if this is observed.
.PP
DNS query capture
.RB ( dns_query
field) works for connected UDP sockets (the common case with glibc's resolver
and
.BR dig (1)).
Resolvers that use
.BR sendto (2)
on an unconnected socket will not have the
.I dns_query
field populated.
.PP
UDP flows use
.B udp_destroy_sock
as the close event.
The timestamp on a UDP
.B flow_short
record reflects when the socket was destroyed, which may be after the last
datagram was sent or received.
.
.SH SECURITY
.SS eBPF safety
The eBPF program embedded in
.B procflow
is validated by the Linux kernel verifier before it is loaded.
The verifier enforces memory safety, bounded execution, and correct register
use; the program cannot crash the kernel, escape its sandbox, or access
arbitrary kernel memory.
The tool is read-only by design: it observes events but does not modify
kernel state or network traffic.
.PP
.SS Log file sensitivity
The log file contains authenticated usernames, process names, command lines,
PIDs, and full connection metadata.
It is created with mode
.B 640
(read-write for root, read-only for the
.I adm
group) regardless of the process umask.
Do not relax these permissions.
Treat the log file with the same care as
.IR /var/log/auth.log .
.PP
.SS Protecting the binary
.B procflow
embeds eBPF C source code that is compiled and loaded into the kernel at
startup.
If an unprivileged user can modify the binary at
.IR /usr/bin/procflow ,
they can inject arbitrary kernel-mode code the next time the service starts.
The installed binary is owned
.B root:root
with mode
.B 755
(not writable by non-root).
Verify this after install:
.PP
.RS
.B ls \-l /usr/bin/procflow
.RE
.PP
.SS Capability bounding
The systemd service sets
.B CapabilityBoundingSet
to restrict the process to only the capabilities required for BPF loading and
/proc reading
.RB ( CAP_SYS_ADMIN ,
.BR CAP_BPF ,
.BR CAP_PERFMON ,
.BR CAP_SYS_PTRACE ).
Even though the process runs as root, it cannot exercise capabilities outside
this set.
.PP
On Linux 5.8 and later,
.B CAP_BPF
and
.B CAP_PERFMON
were split from
.BR CAP_SYS_ADMIN .
Future versions of this package may drop
.B CAP_SYS_ADMIN
from the bounding set on systems that support the finer-grained capabilities.
.PP
.SS What procflow cannot do
Despite running as root, the hardened service unit prevents
.B procflow
from: loading kernel modules, modifying cgroup settings, accessing user home
directories, acquiring real-time scheduling priority, changing its execution
domain via
.BR personality (2),
reading the kernel log buffer, creating new namespaces, or using address
families other than AF_UNIX, AF_INET, and AF_INET6.
.
